In Defense of Bubbles
A Trump Bubble might sound alarming. After all, both Trump and bubbles get =
a bad rap, both at least partially deserved.=C2=A0
When you hear the word =E2=80=9Cbubble,=E2=80=9D you might think, =E2=80=9C=
Overinflated thing that is bound to pop.=E2=80=9D The word has negative con=
notations, earned in particular by the bad bubbles. But those aren=E2=80=99=
t the only bubbles. In Boom [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3db26a4-ee52-4=
48f-a3f3-d5c1d0e9c5a9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Byrne and Tobias distinguish between the two kinds:
Mean-reversion bubble:=C2=A0 =E2=80=9Cthe basic bet is that the future will=
 continue along present trends.=E2=80=9D Think: the mortgage crisis. If you=
 bet that the future will look mostly the same, you can take on debt to lev=
er up your bet.=C2=A0
Inflection bubble: =E2=80=9Cinvestors decide that the future will be meanin=
gfully different from the past.=E2=80=9D Think: the dot-com bubble. If you =
think that the future will look meaningfully different, you buy equity in t=
he things you think will benefit most from the difference.=C2=A0
Inflection bubbles, they argue, drive progress. Their argument is similar t=
o the one I made in Infinity Missions [ https://substack.com/redirect/24521=
4d1-bfb4-47da-9f73-a2deddecca1a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: bubbles attract resources to important projects =
that would not make sense to fund or work on under a normal cost-benefit an=
alysis.=C2=A0
Take the Apollo Program:=C2=A0
When President John F. Kennedy declared in May 1961 that =E2=80=9Cthis nati=
on should commit itself to achieving the goal, before this decade is out, o=
f landing a man on the Moon,=E2=80=9D no one knew how to do it. Rockets, la=
unchpads, space suits, hardware, software, zero-gravity food =E2=80=93 they=
 didn=E2=80=99t exist, and there were no experts in these domains=E2=80=A6
It wasn=E2=80=99t just that the space program lacked what was necessary to =
get to the Moon =E2=80=93 scientists weren=E2=80=99t even sure it was possi=
ble.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe Manhattan Project succeeded because definite optimists were po=
wered along by bubble dynamics,=E2=80=9D they write. =E2=80=9CThe same coul=
d be said of Apollo.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Bubbles pull the future forward by concentrating tremendous amounts of fina=
ncial and human capital on very specific visions of the future, and allowin=
g for otherwise-wasteful exploration and parallelization in the pursuit of =
making it a reality.
Things that may not have happened - ever - without a bubble, happen rapidly=
 with them.=C2=A0
Byrne and Tobias make a compelling case that Moore=E2=80=99s Law itself is =
responsible for Moore=E2=80=99s Law: =E2=80=9CThe industry has exhibited th=
e classic bubble behavior in which predictions about the future =E2=80=93 p=
articularly bold and nearly indefensible ones =E2=80=93 end up driving beha=
viors that make those predictions come true.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Expectations that chips would continue to improve let people design product=
s that would take advantage of better chips which let chipmakers know that =
there would be demand which spurred the investment that made chips improve.=
=C2=A0
In other words, a sufficiently compelling vision can bring itself about. As=
 Stripe Press plasters on Boom=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3=
db26a4-ee52-448f-a3f3-d5c1d0e9c5a9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] website [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3db26=
a4-ee52-448f-a3f3-d5c1d0e9c5a9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9COptimism can be a self-fulfilling prophe=
cy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As Peter Thiel noted and Byrne and Tobias reinforce, however, not all optim=
ism is good, either. Indefinite optimism =E2=80=93 just assuming things wil=
l always go well =E2=80=93 is as destructive as pessimism. Which is why the=
 first common trait among productive bubbles is definite optimism: the beli=
ef that the future will be better backed up by concrete plans to make it so=
