Make requirements less dumb =E2=86=92 Regulatory reform (ex: NEPA, NRC)=C2=
=A0
Delete parts/processes =E2=86=92 Eliminate agencies like the Department of =
Education=C2=A0
Simplify/optimize =E2=86=92 Streamline remaining processes
Accelerate cycle time =E2=86=92 Speed up approvals
Automate =E2=86=92 Modernize government systems
This might break things! SpaceX=E2=80=99s rockets occasionally blow up.=C2=
=A0
Maybe it turns out that the Department of Education, despite America=E2=80=
=99s poor recent performance in public education, actually fulfills a cruci=
al role. Add it, or something like it, back!=C2=A0
I think we=E2=80=99ll be surprised, though (or maybe we won=E2=80=99t) with=
 just how much there is to streamline and optimize, and just how smoothly t=
hings run when you do. People are excited =E2=80=93 filled with thymos, or =
=E2=80=9Cspiritedness,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 precisely because this is the fir=
st administration in a long time that they believe will actually try to pus=
h the limits and see where it breaks.=C2=A0
More than anything, though, a willingness to break things is a return to em=
bracing risk.=C2=A0
Right in Chapter 1, Byrne and Tobias call out risk aversion as a main sourc=
e of stagnation. =E2=80=9CWhat these symptoms of stagnation and decline hav=
e in common is that they result from societal aversion to risk, which has b=
een on the rise for the past few decades,=E2=80=9D they write.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s an argument I made in Riskophilia [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/c46843ff-6315-4cbb-adbe-cfd3b27765b1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which I concluded by saying:
I refuse to believe that America=E2=80=99s best days are behind it. Decline=
 is not inevitable. But it takes more than tech. It=E2=80=99s up to all of =
us to cut through the cruft, get back to the sense of freedom and adventure=
 that make the country great, and build from there.=C2=A0
Go do that risky thing you=E2=80=99ve been putting off. Now. Build the musc=
le. Spread the word: we=E2=80=99re going risk-on.
The only way out is up, even if it=E2=80=99s a little risky up there.
Now, the newly elected government is promising to cut through the cruft and=
 get back to the sense of freedom and adventure that make the country great=
, even if it means breaking some things on the way. Like any good bubble, i=
t=E2=80=99s risk-on.=C2=A0
Risk On
Sometimes, as a writer, you get lucky. I couldn=E2=80=99t have asked for a =
better cherry on top of my analysis than President Trump announcing that El=
on and Vivek would be running the Department of Government Efficiency the n=
ight before hitting send on this piece, after I=E2=80=99d written the draft=
=2E=C2=A0
He wrote that DOGE has the potential to be =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The Manhattan =
Project=E2=80=99 of our time, and after reading this, I hope you have a bet=
ter sense of why that might actually be true. As I noted, it might actually=
 be underselling it: the Trump Bubble could be the bubble that makes bubble=
s.=C2=A0
The DOGE, according to Trump, will =E2=80=9Cpave the way for my Administrat=
ion to dismantle Government Bureaucracy, slash excess regulations, cut wast=
eful expenditures, and restructure Federal Agencies.=E2=80=9D It will, =E2=
=80=9Ccreate an entrepreneurial approach to Government never seen before,=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cliberate our Economy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
It aims, in other words, to fix the machine that builds the machines that b=
uilds the machines.=C2=A0
Do you understand why people are getting so excited? In the last section, I=
 wrote about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s process for fixing the machines that build=
 the machines. Even I thought it was too on the nose. Then just after I fin=
ish writing that, Trump appoints Elon Musk himself to co-lead the organizat=
ion responsible for fixing the machine that builds the machines that builds=
 the machines. Elon is the best person you could get for the job, and he to=
ok the job.=C2=A0
While many people have pointed out that DOGE has no real authority, that it=
 can only make recommendations, that kind of misses the point.=C2=A0
The point is that people on both sides of the aisle believe that the govern=
ment might actually become more efficient. Even if Elon and Vivek can=E2=80=
=99t unilaterally (bilaterally?) decide to cut agencies and regulations, th=
ey can at the very least shine a light on where the Federal Government is p=
articularly wasteful [ https://substack.com/redirect/d0caf26f-8803-45fb-bee=
0-c8d925481f83?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] and create pressure for change through the people.=C2=A0
For the first time in a long time, people feel like they have the chance to=
 participate in making the American machine run better.=C2=A0
Elon tweeted that they=E2=80=99ll be sharing all DOGE actions on X:=C2=A0
And Vivek tweeted that DOGE is going to crowdsource ideas from the people: =
=E2=80=9CAmericans voted for drastic government reform & they deserve to be=
 part of fixing it.=C2=A0
This is exactly what I=E2=80=99m talking about. Like any good bubble, it=E2=
=80=99s participatory.
People will feel like they can actually fix the government, so they=E2=80=
=99ll put more effort into actually trying to fix the government. That migh=
t come in the form of submitting ideas, and it might come in the form of ca=
lling their Congresspeople to push them to enact DOGE=E2=80=99s recommendat=
ions.=C2=A0
The involvement of the people will make it more likely that DOGE succeeds i=
n streamlining the machine, which makes it easier for entrepreneurs to star=
t companies assuming the machine will be fixed, which means more people wil=
l try to start companies to fix problems that they see.=C2=A0
Whether this is exactly how it plays out or not is of secondary importance.=
 In forming the bubble, the important part is that people believe this is h=
ow it will play out, which shapes their actions.=C2=A0
Those things feel squishy, but they=E2=80=99re real. They can turn into a s=
elf-fulfilling prophecy.=C2=A0
I guess one reason I=E2=80=99m writing this is so that you feel a little of=
 the FOMO yourself, so that we can all work on this American project togeth=
er. Bubbles work best when they grow.=C2=A0
Whoever you voted for and however you feel about the results of the electio=
n, there is now a clear choice: you can spend your time wallowing and miss =
out on what may be the greatest opportunity to build in America since the S=
econd Industrial Revolution, or you can get to work and build.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s another thing that=E2=80=99s surprised me, just how non-part=
isan this feels. The line is not Democrat vs. Republican, but those who thi=
nk the American people can make America, and the world, better and those wh=
o think we need government bureaucracy to do it for us.=C2=A0
To whit, in response to the DOGE announcement, Box CEO Aaron Levie, who voc=
ally supported Kamala, tweeted last night [ https://substack.com/redirect/c=
cea1aa2-d72d-46d8-9873-548d02f454a3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s significant opportu=
nity to make the government more capable of delivering for Americans, and i=
ronically it will actually cost less not more.=E2=80=9D
Earlier in the day, he tweeted [ https://substack.com/redirect/7dcc7a83-356=
0-4794-9e87-0f9cee671c87?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CAmerica could enter a supercycle of growth in =
manufacturing, energy, housing, innovation, and more with the right policie=
s going forward.=E2=80=9D
Whatever bitterness and divisions people feel, I think it=E2=80=99s time to=
 let them go. This is bigger than politics.=C2=A0
No one likes paying more taxes to fund wasteful bureaucracy. No one likes f=
eeling like their country is broken and there=E2=80=99s nothing they can do=
 about it. No one likes things going 100x more slowly than they should or c=
osting 100x more than they should. We can all agree on a lot.=C2=A0
The American machine, for all its flaws, is the best the world has built so=
 far, and we=E2=80=99ve never had a better chance to make it run even bette=
r. The ramifications if we do =E2=80=93 cheaper energy, better goods, faste=
r travel, more potent drugs, and much, much more =E2=80=93 benefit everyone=
=2E=C2=A0
This is a meta-bubble that could spawn inflection bubbles for decades to co=
me.=C2=A0
Welcome to the Trump Bubble. The American Millennium [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/a633f2ed-85d3-42b7-8eac-42a5879fc769?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] starts now.=C2=A0
Thanks to Byrne and Tobias for writing Boom, to Claude for editing, and to =
any of you reading this for reading this far with an open mind.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. If you have a little time, to say thanks to o=
ur sponsor and Make Yourself Healthy Again, check out TrueMed [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/385b73d2-9bb0-4b79-a1c3-afd226542ee1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. We=E2=80=99ll be back in=
 your inbox with a Weekly Dose on Friday.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

